{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563667"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16845"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16845"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.42,0.12,0.19,0.2,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67290"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9535"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16845"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52742"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1314"},{"type":"tags","id":"1507"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4164"},{"type":"tags","id":"4828"},{"type":"tags","id":"12807"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32290"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67290","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67290"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with vaginal bleeding and a positive pregnancy test. She reports heavy bleeding with clots for the past two days. Her last menstrual period was eight weeks ago. She has had three previous terminations of pregnancy, all managed medically. She also had a previous miscarriage at 8 weeks managed with misoprostol and found that experience traumatic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals mild suprapubic tenderness. Transvaginal ultrasound shows an intrauterine pregnancy with gestational sac 30mm, fetal pole 10mm with no fetal heart rate seen. Serum beta human chorionic gonadotropin is 8500 IU/L (\u0026gt;5 indicates pregnancy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer preference is for surgical management of miscarriage but is concerned about the risks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In consenting this patient for a suction D\u0026C, what is the risk of Asherman\u0027s syndrome that should be discussed?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["1%","0.1%","10%","5%","20%"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a likely incomplete miscarriage and has concerns about developing Asherman\u0027s syndrome (intrauterine adhesions) following surgical management. Understanding the risk is important for informed consent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1%\u003C/strong\u003E represents the approximate risk of developing intrauterine adhesions after a single, uncomplicated dilatation and curettage (D\u0026amp;C). This risk is considered relatively low when the procedure is performed by an experienced operator using appropriate technique.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA risk of \u003Cstrong\u003E0.1%\u003C/strong\u003E is too low and underestimates the potential for adhesion formation following uterine instrumentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E5%\u003C/strong\u003E is higher than the risk from a single routine D\u0026amp;C, though this level of risk might be more appropriate in cases with multiple previous procedures or other risk factors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E10%\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003E20%\u003C/strong\u003E are much higher than the typical risk for a single procedure. However, these figures may be more representative of the cumulative risk in patients who have undergone multiple D\u0026amp;Cs or who have other risk factors such as postpartum curettage or procedures performed within 4 weeks of pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe risk of Asherman\u0027s syndrome increases with the number of procedures performed, particularly if they are done in close succession or in the context of pregnancy. Other risk factors include postpartum haemorrhage requiring curettage, missed miscarriage, and genital tuberculosis. Prevention strategies include careful surgical technique, minimising trauma to the basalis layer of the endometrium, and considering medical management options where appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The risk of Asherman\u0027s syndrome after a single routine dilatation and curettage is approximately 1%.","Multiple uterine instrumentation procedures increase the risk of intrauterine adhesions.","Risk factors for Asherman\u0027s syndrome include postpartum curettage and procedures performed within 4 weeks of pregnancy."],"references":["Smikle C, Yarrarapu SNS, Khetarpal S. Asherman Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448088/","Conforti, A., Alviggi, C., Mollo, A. et al. The management of Asherman syndrome: a review of literature. Reprod Biol Endocrinol 11, 118 (2013). https://doi.org/10.1186/1477-7827-11-118"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52742"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16845"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52742","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52742"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T18:59:17+10:30